(47, '1.67 ASP SHMC UV420', '', '500', 100, 'product-featured-47.jpg', '<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 7.5pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Roboto;color:#333333\">Why\r\nchoose </span><span lang=\"ZH-CN\" style=\"font-size:10.5pt;font-family:DengXian;\r\nmso-ascii-theme-font:minor-fareast;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\r\nmso-hansi-theme-font:minor-fareast;color:#333333\">1.67 ASP SHMC UV420</span><span lang=\"ZH-CN\" style=\"font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Roboto;color:#333333\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Roboto;color:#333333\">Single vision\r\nlenses&nbsp;?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 7.5pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Roboto;color:#333333\">The\r\neffects of staring at a screen are obvious. Tired and watery eyes, headaches,\r\nblurred vision, and red eyes from excessive friction. Blue light from computer\r\nscreens and digital devices can reduce contrast and cause digital eye strain,\r\nfatigue, dry eyes and discomfort. In addition to this, prolonged exposure to\r\nblue light can cause retinal damage to photoreceptor cells.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 10.5pt;\"><br></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Roboto; font-size: 10.5pt;\">1.Natural\r\nColours - Even though UV 420 lenses filter higher range of blue light, it\r\ndoesn\'t affect the colour of the lenses (NO yellowish tint) and does not change\r\nhow colours appear.</span><br></p><p style=\"margin: 0cm; background-im